    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Food-goblins,\" you say? Well, they are certainly *energetic* little things! If you have too much of those reactive sugars, or if you push the heat too high for too long, yes, you risk burning. This is where the process shifts from the complex, flavorful Maillard reaction into simple caramelization, and then into outright scorching.\n\nThe key to keeping it from getting out of control is managing the heat and the moisture, much like trying to herd a horde of tiny, hungry, and slightly volatile goblins. If the surface gets too dry and too hot, those sugars will break down too rapidly, leading to bitter, acrid flavors—the culinary equivalent of a goblin stampede gone wrong. You want a controlled, steady heat, not a sudden, fiery explosion.",
